so in the area surrounding us, there are a whole bunch of upsidedown jellyfish. they are roughly the size of dinner plates, and just sit upsidedown on the ground under mangroves. They go through photosynthesis just like corals do with the same type of algae
we (read: I) just discovered that there is a nudibranch (sea slug) that lives inside the bodies of these guys. It's previously been identified, but was not known to be here.
and little research has been done on them

they exclusively live in these. not only that, but they eat the tentacles and lay their eggs in them. We are going to test if these guys are absorbing the algae so that they can photosynthesize as well
because nudibranchs do that with stinging cells, but this would be groundbreaking if they steal zooxanthellae (this type of algae) as well
